{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563818"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:05:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:05:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16883"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16883"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.18,0.38,0.06,0.33]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9573"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67449"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9573","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9573"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16883"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52901"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4355"},{"type":"tags","id":"4513"},{"type":"tags","id":"12144"},{"type":"tags","id":"12800"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22598"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67449"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman is being followed in the antenatal clinic with a monochorionic diamniotic twin pregnancy. She presents for review at 34 weeks gestation. This has been an uncomplicated pregnancy with normal serial growth scans showing concordant growth. Both twins are in cephalic presentation. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy supplements. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Symphysial-fundal height measures 38 cm. Fetal heart rates are 140/min and 144/min.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate gestational age range for planned delivery?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["34+0 to 34+6 weeks","38+0 to 38+6 weeks","37+0 to 37+6 weeks","35+0 to 35+6 weeks","36+0 to 36+6 weeks"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario describes an uncomplicated monochorionic diamniotic (MCDA) twin pregnancy where timing of delivery needs to be optimised to balance the risks of prematurity against the risks of continuing the pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E36+0 to 36+6 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is the optimal timing for delivery of uncomplicated MCDA twins. This timing is supported by evidence showing no increase in serious neonatal adverse outcomes compared to later delivery, while avoiding the increased risk of fetal death that occurs with prolonging pregnancy beyond 37 weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDelivery at \u003Cstrong\u003E34+0 to 34+6 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E would be too early for an uncomplicated MCDA pregnancy, exposing the twins to unnecessary risks of prematurity including respiratory distress syndrome and feeding difficulties.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESimilarly, \u003Cstrong\u003E35+0 to 35+6 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E would still be earlier than necessary for an uncomplicated MCDA pregnancy, though this timing might be appropriate if there were complications such as growth discordance or twin-to-twin transfusion syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EContinuing the pregnancy to \u003Cstrong\u003E37+0 to 37+6 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003E38+0 to 38+6 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E would expose the twins to an unnecessary increased risk of fetal death. The shared placental circulation in MCDA twins means that the death of one twin can lead to acute exsanguination of the surviving twin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe mode of delivery should be determined by the usual obstetric indications. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Monochorionic diamniotic twin pregnancies should be delivered between 36+0 and 36+6 weeks gestation to optimise outcomes. This differs to Dichorionic diamniotic twin pregnancies that can usually be delivered at a slightly later gestation (37+0 - 37+6)","Continuing monochorionic diamniotic twin pregnancies beyond 37 weeks increases the risk of fetal death.","Vaginal delivery can be considered for monochorionic diamniotic twins if both are cephalic with no other contraindications however both twins require careful monitoring as there is the possibility of intrapartum twin to twin transfusion."],"references":["National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE). Twin and triplet pregnancy [Internet]. London: NICE; 2019 [cited 2024 Dec 4]. Available from: https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng137/resources/twin-and-triplet-pregnancy-pdf-66141724389829."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52901"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16883"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52901"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-05T14:39:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-05T14:40:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9573"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67449"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","